President Trump addressed the issue of the opioid crisis during a briefing at Trump National Golf Club in Bedminster, New Jersey. He acknowledged that the problem of drug addiction affects people from all walks of life and is the leading cause of accidental death in the United States. He expressed concern that federal drug prosecutions have decreased in recent years and vowed to increase efforts to combat drug trafficking. President Trump emphasized the importance of prevention and education in order to keep people from abusing drugs. He also stressed the need for strong law enforcement to protect communities from drug dealers. The President mentioned the role of the southern border and international cooperation in addressing drug trafficking. He expressed confidence in the ability of healthcare and law enforcement experts to fight the opioid epidemic. The briefing concluded with President Trump's response to a question about North Korea, where he warned that any further threats to the United States would be met with "fire and fury."